{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619732"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:35:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:35:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16574"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16574"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.07,0.03,0.73,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9265"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75724"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9265"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16574"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61242"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1646"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7106"},{"type":"tags","id":"10346"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21952"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75724"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECerebrospinal fluid (CSF) flows through the ventricular system of the brain, starting in the lateral ventricles and eventually reaching the subarachnoid space. Hydrocephalus occurs when there is abnormal accumulation of CSF.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a cause of obstructive hydrocephalus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arachnoid granulation dysfunction","Meningeal inflammation","Choroid plexus papilloma","Cerebral aqueduct stenosis","Superior sagittal sinus thrombosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebral aqueduct stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E, which causes a mechanical blockage of CSF flow between the third and fourth ventricles. This narrow channel is particularly susceptible to obstruction, leading to CSF accumulation upstream of the blockage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent causes of communicating (non-obstructive) hydrocephalus:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArachnoid granulation dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E - Impairs CSF absorption but does not block ventricular flow\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningeal inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - Affects CSF absorption in the subarachnoid space\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChoroid plexus papilloma\u003C/strong\u003E - Causes CSF overproduction without mechanical obstruction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior sagittal sinus thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E - Reduces CSF absorption by increasing venous pressure\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn obstructive hydrocephalus, CSF accumulates due to a physical blockage within the ventricular system, while in communicating hydrocephalus, the problem lies with CSF production or absorption despite patent CSF pathways.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Obstructive hydrocephalus occurs when cerebrospinal fluid flow is blocked within the ventricular system.","The cerebral aqueduct is a common site of obstruction in hydrocephalus due to its narrow diameter.","Non-obstructive (communicating) hydrocephalus results from impaired CSF absorption or overproduction rather than mechanical blockage."],"references":["Xian Z, Fung SH, Nakawah MO. Obstructive hydrocephalus due to aqueductal stenosis from developmental venous anomaly draining bilateral medial thalami: a case report. Radiol Case Rep. 2020 Apr 8;15(6):730-732. doi: 10.1016/j.radcr.2020.02.014. PMID: 32300468; PMCID: PMC7152591.","Rekate HL. The definition and classification of hydrocephalus: a personal recommendation to stimulate debate. Cerebrospinal Fluid Res. 2008 Jan 22;5:2. doi: 10.1186/1743-8454-5-2. PMID: 18211712; PMCID: PMC2263019.","Krishnamurthy S, Li J. New concepts in the pathogenesis of hydrocephalus. Transl Pediatr. 2014 Jul;3(3):185-94. doi: 10.3978/j.issn.2224-4336.2014.07.02. PMID: 26835336; PMCID: PMC4729848."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61242"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16574"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61242"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T20:31:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T20:32:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9265"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75724"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/